<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<handout>
  <title>Worksheet 1.2, Row Reduction and Echelon Forms</title>

  <ul marker="">
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(1) &#160; <em>Written Explanation Exercise</em> Answer each of the following in one or two sentences.</p>
      <ol marker="(a)">
        <p>What are some differences between echelon form and row‑reduced echelon form (RREF)? Give at least three.</p>
        <p>How can row reduction be used to determine whether an augmented matrix corresponds to a consistent system?</p>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(2) &#160; Which matrices are in RREF? Which are in echelon form?</p>
      <p>
        <m>
        A = \begin{pmatrix}0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3\end{pmatrix},\quad
        B = \begin{pmatrix}
            1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\
            0 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 &amp; 0 \\
            0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
        \end{pmatrix},\quad
        C = \begin{pmatrix}
            0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
            1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
            5 &amp; 5 &amp; 0
        \end{pmatrix}
        </m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(3) &#160; List all <m>3 \times 2</m> matrices in RREF. Use <m>\ast</m> for arbitrary entries.</p>
    </li>

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(4) &#160; Indicate whether the following statements are true or false.</p>
      <ol marker="(a)">
        <p>A linear system whose <m>3 \times 5</m> coefficient matrix has three pivot columns must be consistent.</p>
        <p>The echelon form of a coefficient matrix is unique.</p>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(5) &#160; Construct the quadratic polynomial <m>p(t) = a_0 + a_1 t + a_2 t^2</m> passing through <m>(1,12)</m>, <m>(2,15)</m>, and <m>(3,16)</m>.</p>

      <p>
        <me>
        \begin{aligned}
          p(1) \amp= 12 = a_0 + a_1 + a_2 \\
          p(2) \amp= 15 = a_0 + 2a_1 + 4a_2 \\
          p(3) \amp= 16 = a_0 + 3a_1 + 9a_2
        \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>(The coefficient matrix is a Vandermonde matrix.)</p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</handout>